{"id":"quant-ph/0411074","submitter":"Masanao Ozawa","authors":"Masanao Ozawa","title":"Universal uncertainty principle and quantum state control under\n  conservation laws","comments":"4 pages, to appear in the Proceedings of the Seventh International\n  Conference on Quantum Communication, Measurement and Computing","journal-ref":"Proc. 7th Int. Conf. on Quantum Communication, Measurement and\n  Computing, AIP Conference Proceedings 734, 95-98 (2004)","doi":"10.1063/1.1834391","report-no":null,"categories":"quant-ph","license":null,"abstract":"  Heisenberg's uncertainty principle, exemplified by the gamma ray thought\nexperiment, suggests that any finite precision measurement disturbs any\nobservables noncommuting with the measured observable. Here, it is shown that\nthis statement contradicts the limit of the accuracy of measurements under\nconservation laws originally found by Wigner in 1950s, and should be modified\nto correctly derive the unavoidable noise caused by the conservation law\ninduced decoherence. The obtained accuracy limit leads to an interesting\nconclusion that a widely accepted, but rather naive, physical encoding of\nqubits for quantum computing suffers significantly from the decoherence induced\nby the angular momentum conservation law.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 10 Nov 2004 10:38:18 GMT"}],"update_date":"2010-04-28"}
